clinical_study.brief_title: A Study of Two Different Dose Combinations of Nivolumab in Combination With Ipilimumab in Subjects With Previously Untreated, Unresectable or Metastatic Melanoma
clinical_study.official_title: Phase IIIb/IV, Randomized, Double Blinded, Study of Nivolumab 3 mg/kg in Combination With Ipilimumab 1 mg/kg vs Nivolumab 1 mg/kg in Combination With Ipilimumab 3 mg/kg in Subjects With Previously Untreated, Unresectable or Metastatic Melanoma

brief_summary.textblock: The purpose of this study is to evaluate two different dose combinations of nivolumab and ipilimumab in the treatment of melanoma.

study_design_info.masking: Quadruple (Participant, Care Provider, Investigator, Outcomes Assessor)

primary_outcome.measure: Percentage of Participants With Drug-related Grade 3 - 5 Adverse Events (AEs)
primary_outcome.time_frame: After first dose of study treatment and within 30 days of the last dose of study treatment
primary_outcome.description: The drug-related Grade 3 - 5 AE rate was defined as number of participants who experienced at least 1 AE of Grade 3 or higher, judged to be related to study drug by the investigator, and with onset on or after the first dose of study treatment and within 30 days of the last dose of study treatment, divided by number of treated participants. AE grade was defined using National Cancer Institute Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events (NCI CTCAE) version 4.0 criteria

secondary_outcome.measure: Objective Response Rate (ORR)
secondary_outcome.time_frame: From date of randomization to date of objectively documented progression per RECIST 1.1 or the date of subsequent anti-cancer therapy, whichever occurs first (assessed up to April 2018, approximately 20 months)
secondary_outcome.description: The ORR was defined as the number of participants with a best overall response (BOR) of a complete response (CR) or partial response (PR) divided by the number of treated participants for each arm. The BOR was defined as the best response designation, as determined by the Investigator, recorded between the date of randomization and the date of progression, as assessed by the Investigator per RECIST 1.1 or the date of subsequent anticancer therapy (including tumor-directed radiotherapy and tumor-directed surgery), whichever occurred first. For participants without evidence of RECIST 1.1 progression or subsequent anticancer therapy, all available response designations contributed to the BOR assessment. Tumor assessments are scheduled to be performed at Week 12 following randomization, every 8 weeks for the first 12 months and then every 12 weeks until disease progression

secondary_outcome.measure: Overall Survival (OS) Rate
secondary_outcome.time_frame: From date of randomization until the date of first documented progression or date of death from any cause, whichever came first, assessed up to October 2018, approximately 28 months
secondary_outcome.description: OS is defined as the time between the date of randomization and the date of death due to any cause. A participant who has not died will be censored at the last known alive date. OS will be followed continuously while participants are on the study drug and every 3 months via in-person or phone contact after participants discontinue the study drug

secondary_outcome.measure: Median Overall Survival
secondary_outcome.time_frame: From date of randomization to date of death due to any cause (assessed up to April 2018, approximately 20 months)
secondary_outcome.description: OS is defined as the time between the date of randomization and the date of death due to any cause. The results here do not account for any censoring of the data. OS will be followed continuously while participants are on the study drug and every 3 months via in-person or phone contact after participants discontinue the study drug

secondary_outcome.measure: Rate of Progression Free Survival (PFS) at 6 Months
secondary_outcome.description: PFS is defined as the time between the date of randomization and the first date of documented progression, as determined by the investigator, or death due to any cause, whichever occurs first. Participants who die without a reported progression will be considered to have progressed on the date of their death. Particpants who did not progress or die will be censored on the date of their last evaluable tumor assessment. Participants who did not have any on study tumor assessments and did not die will be censored on their date of randomization. Participants who started anti-cancer therapy without a prior reported progression will be censored on the date of their last evaluable tumor assessment prior to the initiation of subsequent anti-cancer therapy

secondary_outcome.measure: Mean Changes From Baseline in the European Organization for Research and Treatment of Cancer Quality of Life Questionnaire (EORTC-QLQ-30) Physical Functioning Scale
secondary_outcome.description: Health Related Quality of Life (HRQoL) was assessed using the EORTC QLQ-C30 questionnaire. The EORTC QLQ-C30 comprises 6 functional scales (role function, physical functioning, cognitive functioning, emotional functioning, social functioning and global quality of life) as well as nine symptom scales (fatigue, pain, nausea/vomiting, dyspnea, insomnia, appetite loss, constipation, diarrhea, and financial difficulties). With the exception of 2 items included in the global health/quality of life scale, for which responses range from 1 (Very poor) to 7 (Excellent), item responses range from 1 (Not at all) to 4 (Very much). Raw scores for the EORTC QLQ-C30 are transformed to a 0-100 metric such that higher scores for all functional scales and Global Health Status indicate better HRQoL; an increase from baseline indicates improvement in HRQoL compared to baseline.

criteria.textblock:
For more information regarding Bristol-Myers Squibb Clinical Trial participation, please visit www.BMSStudyConnect.com
Inclusion Criteria:
- Subject must have been diagnosed with stage III or/and stage IV histologically confirmed melanoma [per American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) staging system] that is unresectable or metastatic
- Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group (ECOG) performance status of 0-1
- Subject has not been treated by systemic anticancer therapy for unresectable or metastatic melanoma
Exclusion Criteria:
- Subjects with active brain metastases or leptomeningeal metastases
- Subjects with ocular melanoma
- Subjects with active, known or suspected autoimmune disease
Other protocol defined inclusion/exclusion criteria could apply

participant_flow.pre_assignment_details: 481 participants were enrolled, 387 randomized (180 N3I1, 180 N1I3, 27 Cohort C/N6I1), 385 treated (180 N3I1, 178 N1I3, 27 Cohort C/N6I1). Reasons not treated: 1 did not meet study criteria, 1 other reason. Cohort C/N6I1 assessed for exploratory outcome measures not being reported in the Outcome Measures module. Safety data included with AE data.

Participants who die without a reported progression will be considered to have progressed on the date of their death. Participants who did not progress or die will be censored on the date of their last evaluable tumor assessment. Participants who did not have any on study tumor assessments and did not die will be censored on their date of randomization. Participants who started anti-cancer therapy without a prior reported progression will be censored on the date of their last evaluable tumor assessment prior to the initiation of subsequent anti-cancer therapy

analysis.method_desc: Test stratified by PD-L1 expression and M stage at screening as entered into the IVRS

outcome.title: Mean Changes From Baseline in the European Organization for Research and Treatment of Cancer Quality of Life Questionnaire (EORTC-QLQ-30) Physical Functioning Scale
outcome.description: Health Related Quality of Life (HRQoL) was assessed using the EORTC QLQ-C30 questionnaire. The EORTC QLQ-C30 comprises 6 functional scales (role function, physical functioning, cognitive functioning, emotional functioning, social functioning and global quality of life) as well as nine symptom scales (fatigue, pain, nausea/vomiting, dyspnea, insomnia, appetite loss, constipation, diarrhea, and financial difficulties). With the exception of 2 items included in the global health/quality of life scale, for which responses range from 1 (Very poor) to 7 (Excellent), item responses range from 1 (Not at all) to 4 (Very much). Raw scores for the EORTC QLQ-C30 are transformed to a 0-100 metric such that higher scores for all functional scales and Global Health Status indicate better HRQoL; an increase from baseline indicates improvement in HRQoL compared to baseline.

reported_events.time_frame: From first does of study treatment to last dose, plus 30 days (assessed up to April 2018, approximately 12 months).
reported_events.desc: AE=any new unfavorable symptom, sign, or disease that may not have a causal relationship with treatment. SAE=a medical event that at any dose results in death, persistent disability, or drug dependency; is life-threatening, an important medical event, or a birth defect; or requires hospitalization. Treatment-related=having certain, probable, possible, or missing relationship to study drug. Grade (Gr) 1=Mild, Gr 2=Moderate, Gr 3=Severe, Gr 4= Potentially Life-threatening or disabling.

group.title: Nivolumab 3 mg/kg + Ipilimumab 1 mg/kg
group.description: nivolumab 3 mg/kg IV combined with ipilimumab 1 mg/kg IV every 3 weeks for 4 doses then nivolumab (flat dose 480 mg) every 4 weeks

group.title: Nivolumab 1 mg/kg + Ipilimumab 3 mg/kg
group.description: nivolumab 1 mg/kg IV combined with ipilimumab 3 mg/kg IV every 3 weeks for 4 doses then nivolumab (flat dose 480 mg) every 4 weeks

group.title: Nivolumab 6 mg/kg + Ipilimumab 1 mg/kg
group.description: nivolumab 6 mg/kg plus ipilimumab 1 mg/kg followed by nivolumab 480 mg Flat Dose 4 weeks later and repeated every 8 weeks

certain_agreements.restrictive_agreement: Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. agreements with investigators vary; constant is our right to embargo communications regarding trial results prior to public release for a period 60 days from submittal for review. We will not prohibit investigators from publishing, but will prohibit the disclosure of previously undisclosed confidential information other than study results, and request postponement of single-center publications until after disclosure of the clinical trial's primary publication.
